 changing loyalties to the Union and the Confederacy, the book highlights the unequal economic and social impacts of the war, General Sherman’s siege, and the stunning rebirth of the city in postwar years. The final chapter of the book focuses on Atlanta’s historical memory of the Civil War and how racial divisions have led to separate commemorations of the war’s meaning.  afunded by Garamond Agency, Inc.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilians in warzGeorgiazAtlantaxHistoryy19th century. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877)zGeorgiazAtlanta. 0aSocial changezGeorgiazAtlantaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh2 aGaramond Agency, Inc.efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019216240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030020658640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300206586423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300206586/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY